{{Infobox settlement | name = Cipetir | settlement_type = Village | other_name = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image_skyline = | image_alt = | image_caption = | image_flag = | image_shield = | nickname = | motto = | image_map = | map_caption = | image_map1 = | map_caption1 = | pushpin_map = <!-- Netherlands --> | pushpin_label_position = left | pushpin_map_caption = Location in the Netherlands | subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]] | subdivision_name = [[Indonesia]] | subdivision_type1 = [[Regencies of Indonesia|Regency]] | subdivision_name1 = [[Sukabumi]] | subdivision_type2 = [[Districts of Indonesia|District]] | subdivision_name2 = [[Districts of West Java|Kadudampit]] | leader_title = | leader_name = | leader_party = | coordinates = | coordinates_footnotes = | elevation_m = | elevation_min_m = | elevation_max_m = | area_footnotes = | area_total_km2 = | established_title = | established_date = | population_footnotes = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags --> | population_total = 5716 | population_as_of = 2010 | population_demonym = | population_note = | population_density_km2 = auto | timezone = | utc_offset = | timezone_DST = | utc_offset_DST = | postal_code_type = | postal_code = | area_code_type = | area_code = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Cipetir''' (pre-[[Enhanced Indonesian Spelling System|EYD]] spelling and [[Dutch language|Dutch]]: '''Tjipetir''') is a [[village]] in [[Sukabumi Regency|Sukabumi]], [[West Java]], [[Indonesia]]. As of 2010, it has 5,716 inhabitants.<ref>Census 2010, Badan Pusat Statistik, [http://bps.go.id/eng/download_file/Population_of_Indonesia_by_Village_2010.pdf Population_of_Indonesia_by_Village]</ref>
The name comes from [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]], and literally means "Thunder River", from ''ci'' ("river") and ''petir'' ("thunder").
==Plantation== [[File:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Aflevering produkt in blokken van onderneming 'Tjipetir' (Preanger) TMnr 10012863.jpg|thumb|Blocks of rubber product with the TJIPETIR brand visible. Source: [[Tropenmuseum]]]] Cipetir was the site of a [[gutta-percha]] plantation in the 19th and early 20th century.
[[Marine debris]] consisting of blocks of gutta-percha, which is highly resistant to water corrosion, with the word "TJIPETIR" on them has been found on beaches throughout Europe. They are believed to be coming from one or more sunken ships from the early 1900s. The wreck of the ''[[Miyazaki Maru]]'', sank in 1917, has been put forward as potential source of the blocks.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cacciottolo |first=Mario |date=1 December 2014 |title=Tjipetir mystery: Why are rubber-like blocks washing up on European beaches? |publisher=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-30043875 |accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=David |first=Romain |date=2014-04-03 |title=Le mystère des "plaques de Tjipetir" ravive le fantôme du "Titanic" |publisher=Le Figaro |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/2014/04/01/01016-20140401ARTFIG00277-le-mystere-des-plaques-de-tjipetir-ravive-le-fantome-du-titanic.php}}</ref>
{{commons category|Cipetir rubber plantation}}
