==D==

{{glossary}}

{{term|term= deciduous |content= [[deciduous]] }}
{{defn|defn= Dehiscing and falling seasonally, as with bark, leaves, or petals. Compare [[#persistent|persistent]].}}

{{term|term= declinate |content={{vanchor|[[:wikt:declinate|declinate]]}}}}
{{defn|defn= Curving downwards, and then upwards at the tip. Often qualified, e.g. declinate-ascendant.}}

{{term|term= decompound }}
{{defn|defn= Divided to more than one level, e.g. in [[#bipinnate|bipinnate]] leaves, in which the [[#leaflet|leaflets]] of what otherwise would be a pinnate leaf are themselves pinnately divided.}}

{{term|term= decorticate }}
{{defn|defn= To shed or peel off the outer bark of a tree.}}

{{term|term= decumbent }}
{{defn|defn= Having branches growing horizontally along the ground but which are turned up at the ends.}}

{{term|term= decurrent |content= [[decurrent]] }}
{{defn|defn= Extending downwards beyond the point of [[#insertion, point of|insertion]], e.g. when the base of a leaf or a fungal gill is prolonged downwards along the stem in a raised line or narrow wing.}}

{{term|term= decussant }}
{{defn|defn= A synonym for [[#decussate|decussate]]; the usage ''decussant'' is questionable and occurs rarely, probably as an error. The formally correct usage is ''decussate''.}}

{{term|term= decussate |content={{vanchor|[[:wikt:decusssate|decusssate]]}}}}
{{defn|defn= [[#opposite|Opposite]] with successive pairs borne at right angles to the last; generally applied to the arrangement of leaves.}}

{{term|term= definite }}
{{defn|defn= Of a constant number, e.g. twice as many stamens as the petals or sepals (or less), or an inflorescence ending in a flower or an aborted floral bud, typically a cymose inflorescence. Compare [[#indefinite|indefinite]].}}

{{term|term= deflexed }}
{{defn|defn= Bent downwards. Compare [[#inflexed|inflexed]].}}

{{term|term= dehiscent |content= [[dehiscence (botany)|dehiscent]] }}
{{defn|defn= Breaking open at maturity to release contents; refers e.g. to the opening of fruits to release seeds, of anthers to release pollen and of sporangia to release spores. Compare [[#indehiscent|indehiscent]].}}

{{term|term= deltoid |content= [[Delta (letter)|deltoid]] }}
{{defn|defn= Shaped like the uppercase Greek letter '''Δ''', i.e. like a more or less equilateral triangle.}}

{{term|term= dendroid }}
{{defn|defn= Tree-like; branching like a tree.}}

{{term|term= dentate|content= [[Leaf margin|dentate]] }}
{{defn|defn= [[#toothed|Toothed]], especially in reference to leaf [[#margin|margins]].}}

{{term|term= denticulate |content= [[Leaf margin|denticulate]] }}
{{defn|defn= Finely [[#toothed|toothed]]; a diminutive form of [[#dentate|dentate]].}}

{{term|term= deserticolous|content= [[deserticolous]] }}
{{defn|defn= Inhabiting a desert.}}

{{term|term= determinate |content= [[Determinate growth|determinate]] }}
{{defn|defn= Limited, usually in growth. Compare [[#indeterminate|indeterminate]].}}

{{term|term= diaspore |content= [[Diaspore (botany)|diaspore]] }}
{{defn|defn= A reproductive part of a plant, adapted for dispersal and for establishing new plants; a disseminule such as a seed, or specialised buds, branches, inflorescences or fruits.}}

{{term|term= dichasium |content= [[dichasium]] }}
{{defn|defn= A cymose inflorescence with all branches below the terminal flower in [[#regular|regular]] opposite pairs. Compare [[#monochasium|monochasium]].}}

{{term|term= dichlamydeous }}
{{defn|defn= [[perianth]] is divided into separate [[Sepal|calyx]] and [[Petal|corolla]]. Compare to [[#homochlamydeous|homochlamydeous]], in which they are indistinguishable}}

{{term|term= dichotomous |content= [[dichotomy|dichotomous]] }}
{{defn|defn= forking into two equal branches. This may result from an equal division of the growing tip, or may be [[sympodial]], in which the growing tip is aborted and replaced. Typically refers to mode of branch growth, as in ''[[Aloidendron dichotomum]]'', but also to other organs, such as the thorns of various species of ''[[Carissa]]'' (which morphologically are branches) and [[Thallus|thalli]] or [[hypha]]e of various algae and fungi.}}

{{term|term= dicotyledon |content= [[dicotyledon]] }}
{{defn|defn= a flowering plant whose embryo has two (rarely more) cotyledons (seed leaves) (common usage: dicot.) compare [[#monocotyledon|monocotyledon]] (common usage: monocot.).}}

{{term|term= digitate |content= [[Leaf shape|digitate]] }}
{{defn|defn= with segments spreading from a common centre, like the fingers of a hand; see also [[#palmate|palmate]], [[#palmatisect|palmatisect]].}}

{{term|term= dimorphic }}
{{defn|defn= occurring in 2 different forms (in respect to shape and/or size), for example of stamens, [[Frond dimorphism|fronds]], leaves. See also '''[[#monomorphic|monomorphic]]''' (having a single form) and '''[[Polymorphism (biology)|polymorphic]]''' (many forms)}}

{{term|term= dioecious |content= [[dioecious]] }}
{{defn|defn= of vascular plants, when male and female reproductive structures develop on different individuals. cf. [[#monoecious|monoecious]].}}

{{term|term= dioicous |content= [[dioicous]] }}
{{defn|defn= of bryophyte [[#gametophyte|gametophytes]], when male and female reproductive structures develop on different individuals. cf. [[#monoicous|monoicous]].}}

{{term|term= diploid |content= [[Ploidy#diploid|diploid]] }}
{{defn|defn= with two full sets of chromosomes in the nucleus of a [[#sporophyte|sporophyte]] cell, that is one set from each of the parental [[#gamete|gametes]].  This is expressed symbolically as 2n, where n = the number of chromosomes in the [[#haploid|haploid]] gametes.}}

{{term|term= diplostemonous |content= [[stamen|diplostemonous]] }}
{{defn|defn= [[stamens]] arranged in two [[Whorl (botany)|whorls]], with the outer whorl alternating with the [[petals]], while the inner whorl is opposite the petals. Compare [[#obdiplostemonous|obdiplostemonous]].}}

{{term|term= disk |content= [[Glossary of plant morphology#Disk|disk (disc)]] }}
{{defn|defn= a plate or ring of structures derived from the [[#receptacle|receptacle]], and occurring between whorls of floral parts. In some groups, especially [[Sapindales]], the [[nectary]] is in the form of a prominent disk. In [[Asteraceae|daisies]], the central part of the [[#capitulum|capitulum]] is a disk, hence flowers borne there are called disk flowers or florets.}}

{{term|term= discoid }}
{{defn|defn= resembling a disc or plate, having both thickness and parallel faces and with a rounded margin. Also used to describe the flower head of [[Asteraceae]] where there are no ray florets, but only disc florets.}}

{{term|term= discolorous }}
{{defn|defn= Of leaves, with upper and lower surfaces of a different colour.}}

{{term|term= disjunct |content= [[disjunct distribution|disjunct]] }}
{{defn|defn= Occurring in widely separated geographic areas, distinctly separate; applies to a discontinuous range in which one or more populations are separated from other potentially interbreeding populations far enough as to preclude gene flow between them.}}

{{term|term= dissected }}
{{defn|defn= Deeply divided; cut into many segments.}}

{{term|term= distal |content= [[distal]] }}
{{defn|defn= Remote from the point of origin or attachment; the free end. Compare [[#proximal|proximal]].}}

{{term|term= distichous |content= [[phyllotaxis|distichous]] }}
{{defn|defn= Arranged in two opposite rows (and hence in the same plane).}}

{{term|term= distinct }}
{{defn|defn= Separate or free; not united.}}

{{term|term= distyly |content= [[distyly]] }}
{{defn|defn= The condition in which the flowers of a species occur in two forms that differ only by the length of the style and stamens, and flowers of only one of these forms appear on any one plant. see:[[#heterostyly|heterostyly]]}}

{{term|term= diurnal |content= [[Diurnality|diurnal]] }}
{{defn|defn= Of the day; occurring or opening in the daytime.}}

{{term|term= divaricate |content= [[divaricate]] }}
{{defn|defn= Wide-spreading.}}

{{term|term= divergent }}
{{defn|defn= Spreading in different directions, generally upward.}}

{{term|term= division |content= [[division (botany)|division]] }}
{{defn|defn= A taxonomic rank below [[#kingdom|kingdom]] in the standard taxonomic hierarchy; the approximate botanical equivalent of [[#phylum|phylum]], which is used for animals and other kingdoms.}}

[[File:Epipremnum pinnatum var.jpg|thumb|right|Leaves of ''[[Epipremnum aureum]]'' have a '''drip tip''']]
{{term|term= domatia |content= [[domatium|domatia]] }}
{{defn|defn= (sing. ''domatium'') Any hollow structure formed by a plant that is inhabited by animals such as ants or mites.}}

{{term|term= dorsal |content= [[dorsal (location)|dorsal]] }}
{{defn|defn= At the rear or back, facing away from the axis ([[#abaxial|abaxial]]) in a lateral organ or away from the substrate in a prostrate plant.}}

{{term|term= dorsifixed }}
{{defn|defn= Attached at or by the back, e.g. anthers on a filament.}}

{{term|term= dorsiventral |content= [[dorsiventral]] }}
{{defn|defn= Having structurally different upper and lower surfaces, e.g. some leaves.}}

{{term|term= drip tip}}
{{defn|defn= A long, narrow, [[#caudate|caudate]] or [[#acuminate|acuminate]] extension at the tip of a leaf or leaflet.}}

{{term|term= drupe |content= [[drupe]] }}
{{defn|defn= A type of succulent fruit formed from one [[#carpel|carpel]]; the single seed is enclosed by a stony layer of the fruit wall, e.g. in peaches and olives. Also called a [[#kernel|kernel]].}}


{{term|term= drupelet |content= [[drupe]]let }}
{{defn|defn= A small [[#drupe|drupe]] formed from one of the carpels in an [[#apocarpous|apocarpous]] flower. Drupelets usually form a [[compound fruit]], as in ''[[Rubus]]'', but they may become widely separated, as in ''[[Ochna]]''.}}

{{term|term= druse |content= [[Druse (botany)|druse]] }}
{{defn|defn= A globular mass of [[calcium oxalate]] crystals, usually with the crystals radiating from an [[Organic matter|organic]] core.}}

{{glossary end}}

