{{Infobox lake | name = Violet Lake | image = Starr 991130-1185 Metrosideros polymorpha.jpg | caption = Violet Lake situated in a forest of ʻōhiʻa lehua trees (''[[Metrosideros polymorpha]]'') | image_bathymetry = | caption_bathymetry = | location = [[West Maui Mountains]], [[Maui]] | coords = {{coord|20.907471|-156.594779|type:waterbody_globe:earth_region:US-HI|display=inline,title}} | type = | inflow = | outflow = | catchment = | basin_countries = United States | length = | width = | area = {{convert|10x20|ft|m|abbr=on}} (approximate)<ref name="Maui2003">{{cite book|author=West Maui Mountains Watershed Partnership|title=West Maui Mountains Watershed Management Plan|url=http://www.westmauiwatershed.org/UserFiles/WMMWP%20Management%20Plan%20-%20FINAL%2012-11-13.pdf|year=2003|pages=11–18}}</ref><ref name="WestMaui">{{cite web|title=Rare Ecosystems – Ki'owaiokihawahine (Violet Lake)|work=West Maui Mountains Watershed Partnership|url=http://www.westmauiwatershed.org/explore/watersheds/rare-ecosystems|accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref> | depth = | max-depth = | volume = | residence_time = | shore = | elevation = {{convert|5,020|ft|m|abbr=on}} (approximate)<ref>{{cite web|title=Violet Lake|work=TopoZone|url=http://www.topozone.com/hawaii/maui-hi/lake/violet-lake-2/|accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Hawaiian Dictionaries|Violet Lake|HASHdfa7baaadff57417dcfeda|dic=hpn|accessdate=September 24, 2010}}</ref> | islands = | cities = }}
'''Violet Lake''' ({{lang-haw|Kiʻowaiokihawahine}}), is a small high-elevation lake located at {{convert|5,020|ft|m|abbr=on}} above sea level on Mauna Kahalawai (the [[West Maui Mountains]]), situated in the western part of the island of [[Maui]]. It is located in the boggy slopes near the ʻEke Crater and [[Puʻu Kukui]], the highest peak of the West Maui Mountains. It is approximately {{convert|10x20|ft|m|abbr=on}} in size.<ref name="Maui2003" /><ref name="WestMaui" />
The lake's English name derive from the reflected color of the lake's surface and also the Maui [[Viola (plant)|violet]] (''[[Viola mauiensis]]'') which grows on its banks.<ref name="Wianecki">{{cite magazine|last=Wianecki|first=Shannon|title=Rooted in Mystery: A Glimpse into Puʻu Kukui, Maui’s Protected Native Plant Heaven|url=http://mauimagazine.net/rooted-in-mystery/|magazine=Maui Nō Ka ʻOi Magazine|volume=|issue=|date=|publisher=|location=Wailuku|ref=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Pukui|first1=Mary Kawena|authorlink1=Mary Kawena Pukui|last2=Elbert|first2=Samuel H.|authorlink2=Samuel Hoyt Elbert|last3=Mookini|first3=Esther T.|title=Place Names of Hawaii|url=http://ulukau.org/elib/cgi-bin/library?c=pepn&l=en |year=1974|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|location=Honolulu|isbn=978-0-8248-0524-1|oclc=1042464|ref=|page=217}}</ref><ref name="Howe1918">{{cite book|last=MacCaughey|first=Vaughan|editor-last=Taylor|editor-first=Norman|title=The Hawaiian Violaceae|journal=Torreya: A Monthly Journal of Botanical Notes and News|url=https://archive.org/details/jstor-40595842|volume=XVIII|date=January 1918|publisher=Torrey Botanical Society|location=New York|jstor=40595842|oclc=5550601940|ref=|pages=1–11}}</ref> The [[Hawaiian language]] name Kiʻowaiokihawahine means the "pond of Kihawahine".<ref name="Maui2003" /><ref name="WestMaui" /><ref name="Guide">{{cite web|title=Hawaii Natural Area Reserves System|year=2003|url=http://www.conservehi.org/documents/CCH_PosterGuide03.pdf|accessdate=May 27, 2017|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Young|first=Peter T.|title=Kiowaiokihawahine (Violet Lake)|work=Image of Old Hawaiʻi|publisher=Hoʻokuleana LLC|date=February 18, 2015|url=http://imagesofoldhawaii.com/eke-crater/kiowaiokihawahine-violet-lake/|accessdate=May 27, 2017|ref=harv}}</ref>
The lake was important to the traditional [[Hawaiian religion]]. During ancient times, the lake and surrounding summit area was protected by ''[[kapu]]'' and regarded as the meeting place of heaven and earth.<ref name="Maui2003" /><ref name="WestMaui" /> The lake was believed to be the home of the Hawaiian ''moʻo'' (lizard) goddess [[Kihawahine]], who was associated with the [[Alii nui of Maui|''aliʻi nui'']] (high chiefs or kings) of Maui and an ''[[aumakua|ʻaumakua]]'' (family deity) of Queen [[Keōpūolani]], a descendant of the Maui royal line and the highest-ranking wife of King [[Kamehameha I]], who established the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]], and their son [[Kamehameha III]].<ref name="Wianecki" /><ref name="Klieger1998" /> Kihawahine was also associated with the wetland and former royal complex at [[Mokuʻula]] located in the watersheds below the lake in [[Lahaina]].<ref name="Klieger1998">{{cite book|last=Klieger|first=P. Christiaan|title=Mokuʻula: Maui's Sacred Island|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HitzAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=Bishop Museum Press|location=Honolulu|isbn=978-1-58178-002-4|oclc=40142899|pages=7–24}}</ref>
The surrounding [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests|montane rainforest]] ecosystem on the slopes of Puʻu Kukui Watershed Management Area (the second wettest spot in the [[Hawaiian Islands]]) is extremely diverse and home to many endemic species. The lake's own unique ecosystem have not been well studied.<ref name="Wianecki" /><ref name="Percyetal2008">{{cite journal |url=http://www.biology.duke.edu/cunningham/pdfs/PercyMetrosideros2008.pdf |first=Diana M. |last=Percy |author2=Adam M. Garver |author3=Warren L. Wagner |author4=Helen F. James |author5=Clifford W. Cunningham |author6=Scott E. Miller |author7= Robert C. Fleischer |title=Progressive island colonization and ancient origin of Hawaiian Metrosideros (Myrtaceae) |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B |volume=275 |year=2008 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0191 |page=1484 |pmid=18426752 |issue=1642 |pmc=2602662}}</ref> Species include the dwarfed ʻōhiʻa lehua tree (''[[Metrosideros polymorpha]]''), the Maui violet (''Viola mauiensis''), a variety of [[Hawaiian lobelioids]] (''[[Lobelia gloriamontis]]''), the Hawaiian damsel flies (''[[Megalagrion|Megalagrion spp.]]''), and others.<ref name="Maui2003" /><ref name="Wianecki" /> It has been described as an "extremely rare gem" which have "residents and visiting scientists alike".<ref name="Maui2003" /><ref name="WestMaui" />
== See also == * [[List of lakes in Hawaii]]
